s($,"aTC","avK",()=>{var q="proj-001",p="text/markdown"
return A.an(["doc-001",A.ate("# Analysis Report\n\nThis report summarises the flow cytometry analysis performed on the **immunophenotyping** dataset using the Tercen platform.\n\n---\n\n## Overview\n\nThe analysis pipeline processes *high-dimensional* flow cytometry data to identify and characterise immune cell populations. Key steps include compensation, gating, clustering, and visualisation.\n\n> This analysis was generated by the Tercen LLM assistant based on the uploaded FCS files and the selected workflow template.\n\n## Marker Panel\n\n| Marker | Channel | Purpose | Clone |\n|--------|---------|---------|-------|\n| CD3 | FITC | T-cell lineage | OKT3 |\n| CD4 | PE | Helper T-cells | RPA-T4 |\n| CD8 | APC | Cytotoxic T-cells | SK1 |\n| CD19 | PE-Cy7 | B-cell lineage | HIB19 |\n| CD45 | BV421 | Pan-leukocyte | HI30 |\n\n## Results\n\nThe clustering algorithm identified **12 distinct populations** across all samples. The major populations are:\n\n1. CD3+ T-cells (45.2%)\n2. CD19+ B-cells (12.8%)\n3. CD3-CD19- NK cells (8.4%)\n4. Monocytes (15.1%)\n5. Remaining populations (18.5%)\n\n### Key Findings\n\n- The **CD4/CD8 ratio** was within normal range (1.5-2.5) for all healthy controls\n- ~~Previous analysis suggested an elevated CD19 count~~ -- this was corrected after re-gating\n- Sample processing used `flowCore::read.FCS()` for file import\n\n### Scatter Plot\n\n![Population scatter plot](https://tercen.example/api/v1/files/img-scatter-001.png)\n\n### Code Used\n\n```r\nlibrary(flowCore)\nlibrary(FlowSOM)\n\n# Read FCS files\nfs <- read.flowSet(files)\n\n# Compensate\nfs_comp <- compensate(fs, comp_matrix)\n\n# Cluster with FlowSOM\nsom <- FlowSOM(fs_comp, colsToUse = markers)\n```\n\n---\n\n## Conclusion\n\nThe immunophenotyping analysis confirms expected population distributions. For detailed per-sample breakdowns, see the [Data Viewer results](https://tercen.example/project/proj-001/data/results-001).\n\n*Report generated on 2026-03-15 by Tercen LLM Assistant*\n","doc-001",p,"analysis-report.md",q),"doc-002",A.ate("Meeting Notes - Flow Cytometry Project Review\n\nDate: March 15, 2026\nAttendees: Dr. Smith, Dr. Garcia, Martin (Bioinformatics)\n\nSummary of Discussion:\n\nThe team reviewed the current state of the immunophenotyping analysis pipeline. Dr. Smith presented the initial results from the first batch of 24 samples processed through the automated workflow.\n\nKey points discussed:\n\nThe compensation matrix needs to be recalculated using single-stain controls from the March batch. The current matrix was derived from February controls and shows slight spillover in the PE-Cy7 channel.\n\nDr. Garcia suggested implementing a two-stage gating strategy: first gate on viable singlets using FSC/SSC, then apply the FlowSOM clustering on the cleaned population. This approach reduces noise from debris and doublets.\n\nMartin confirmed that the Tercen workflow can be modified to include the additional preprocessing step. The estimated processing time per sample would increase from 2 minutes to approximately 3 minutes.\n\nAction items:\n\nRun single-stain controls on the March samples by end of week.\nUpdate the compensation matrix in the Tercen workflow configuration.\nAdd the two-stage gating step to the pipeline before clustering.\nRe-run the first 24 samples with the updated pipeline for comparison.\nSchedule follow-up review for next Thursday at 2pm.\n\nThe team agreed that once the pipeline is validated with the updated settings, it will be applied to the full cohort of 180 samples. Expected completion: end of March 2026.\n\nAdditional notes from Martin:\n\nThe current Tercen project is set up with three workflows: preprocessing, clustering, and visualisation. Each can be run independently or chained together. The LLM assistant has been configured to generate reports automatically after each workflow completion.\n\nFile storage is within the Tercen project under the reports folder. All generated documents are versioned and can be viewed through the Document Editor or downloaded as markdown files.\n","doc-002","text/plain","notes.txt",q),"doc-003",A.ate('# Pipeline Configuration\n\nThis document describes the configuration for the immunophenotyping analysis pipeline.\n\n## Setup Instructions\n\n1. Create a new Tercen project and upload FCS files\n2. Import the workflow template from the shared library\n3. Configure the compensation matrix (see below)\n4. Set the clustering parameters\n5. Run the pipeline and review results\n\n## Compensation Matrix\n\n```yaml\ncompensation:\n  method: "spillover"\n  source: "single-stain-controls"\n  channels:\n    - FITC\n    - PE\n    - APC\n    - PE-Cy7\n    - BV421\n  auto_calculate: true\n```\n\n## Clustering Parameters\n\n```json\n{\n  "algorithm": "FlowSOM",\n  "parameters": {\n    "xdim": 10,\n    "ydim": 10,\n    "nClusters": 15,\n    "maxMeta": 20,\n    "seed": 42\n  },\n  "markers": ["CD3", "CD4", "CD8", "CD19", "CD45"],\n  "transform": "arcsinh",\n  "cofactor": 150\n}\n```\n\n## Parameter Reference\n\n| Parameter | Type | Default | Description |\n|-----------|------|---------|-------------|\n| xdim | integer | 10 | SOM grid X dimension |\n| ydim | integer | 10 | SOM grid Y dimension |\n| nClusters | integer | 15 | Target number of metaclusters |\n| maxMeta | integer | 20 | Maximum metaclusters |\n| seed | integer | 42 | Random seed for reproducibility |\n| transform | string | arcsinh | Data transformation method |\n| cofactor | number | 150 | Arcsinh cofactor |\n\n## Quality Control Script\n\n```r\n# QC check after clustering\nlibrary(FlowSOM)\n\nqc_results <- list()\nfor (cluster_id in seq_len(nClusters)) {\n  cells <- GetClusters(som) == cluster_id\n  qc_results[[cluster_id]] <- list(\n    count = sum(cells),\n    percentage = mean(cells) * 100,\n    median_markers = apply(data[cells, markers], 2, median)\n  )\n}\n\n# Flag clusters with fewer than 100 cells\nsmall_clusters <- which(sapply(qc_results, function(x) x${\'\'}count < 100))\nmessage(sprintf("Warning: %d clusters have fewer than 100 cells", length(small_clusters)))\n```\n\n## Output Files\n\nThe pipeline generates the following output files:\n\n1. **results.csv** -- per-cell cluster assignments\n2. **summary.md** -- population statistics report\n3. **scatter_plots/** -- PNG visualisations per marker pair\n4. **qc_report.md** -- quality control metrics\n',"doc-003",p,"pipeline-config.md",q)],t.N,t.IU)})
